@NARFNra:  
[Basilisk Collar](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Basilisk Collar) seems the better choice. I'd also force something to block it (e.g. [Lure](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Lure), [Nemesis Mask](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Nemesis Mask), [Provoke](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Provoke), etc). Or you could do it in reverse with [Valor Made Real](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Valor Made Real) and [Siren's Call](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Siren's Call). Oh yeah, ![1](/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&name=1&type=symbol)![White](/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&name=W&type=symbol)![Blue](/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&name=U&type=symbol)![Red](/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&name=R&type=symbol) for a set of four cards to produce some bizarre cross between [Plague Wind](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Plague Wind) and [Multani's Harmony](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Multani's Harmony)!  

It's easy to find a way to prevent the [Swine-Rider](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Swine-Rider) from killing itself (or any other creature you want to keep alive). If they keep tapping all their creatures to avoid having to block (say, by attacking), [Jangling Automaton](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Jangling Automaton) should do the trick.

